Once again, racist attacks are increasing across Europe.
LW: once or twice = a few times
I've seen him once or twice in town.
LW: (every) once in a while = sometimes but not often
We meet for lunch once in a while.
LW: once and for all = completely and in a way that will finally solve a problem
Our intention is to destroy their offensive capability once and for all.
LW: once in a lifetime = only likely to happen once in a person's life
An opportunity as good as this arises once in a lifetime.
LW: the once (UK) = on a single occasion
I've only played rugby the once, and I never want to play it again.
LW: formerly = in the past
The European Union was formerly called the European Community.
LW: suddenly = quickly and unexpectedly
I suddenly realized what I'd said, but it was too late.
LW: shortly = soon
We will shortly be arriving in King's Cross Station.
LW: shortly after/before sth = a short time after or before something
Shortly after you left, a man came into the office looking for you.
LW: whenever = every or any time
Whenever I go there they seem to be asleep.
LW: eventually = in the end, especially after a long time or a lot of effort, problems, etc.
I found it hard to follow what the teacher was saying, and eventually I lost concentration.
LW: meanwhile = until something expected happens, or while something else is happening
Carl's starting college in September. Meanwhile, he's travelling around Europe.
LW: further = (comparative of "far") to a greater distance or degree, or at a more advanced level
I never got further than the first five pages of "Ulysses".
LW: during = from the beginning to the end of a particular period
There were huge advances in aviation technology during the Second World War.
LW: in time = early enough
I got home just in time - it's starting to rain.
LW: prior to = before a particular time or event
the weeks prior to her death
LW: straightaway = immediately
We don't have to go straightaway, do we?
LW: by the time = К моменту
By the time the plan was approved, the country office had already embarked on most of the procurement.
LW: until now = до сих пор
Many Member States have, until now, treated caregiving issues as solely a private, family function.
LW: now that = You use now that to give an explanation of a new situation
Now that I live only a few blocks from work, I walk to work and enjoy it.
LW: instantly = immediately
Both drivers were killed instantly.
LW: presently = now; at the present time
Three sites are presently under consideration for the new hotel.
LW: occasionally = sometimes but not often
Occasionally I'll have a piece of chocolate, but it's very rare.
LW: in the middle =
Osaka returned to tennis in the middle of July.
LW: to the left/right =
Move a little to the left, please.
LW: in front of =
We don't want any unpleasantness in front of the children.
LW: on this side =
No, I'll keep Tommy on this side.
LW: in the distance = at a point that is far away
On a clear day you can see the temple in the distance.
LW: here and there = in different places
There were a few books here and there, but apart from that the room was quite bare.
LW: in the foreground = the people, objects, countryside, etc. in a picture or photograph that seem nearest to you and form its main part
In the foreground of the painting is a horse and cart.
LW: in the background =
The little figure that you can just see in the background of the photograph is me.
LW: in the center of =
Our school is in the center of the town.
LW: adjacent (to) = very near, next to, or touching
They lived in a house adjacent to the railway. / She took a knife and fork from an adjacent table.
LW: opposite (to)  = completely different
You'd never know they're sisters - they're completely opposite to each other in every way.
LW: nearby = not far away
If there's a café nearby, we could stop for a snack.
LW: wherever = to or in any or every place
We can go wherever you like.
LW: around = in a position or direction surrounding, or in a direction going along the edge of or from one part to another (of)
A crowd had gathered around the scene of the accident.
LW: alongside = next to, or together with
The new pill will be used alongside existing medicines.
LW: amid = in the middle of or surrounded by
On the floor, amid mounds of books, were two small envelopes.
LW: beneath = in or to a lower position than someone or something, under someone or something
After weeks at sea, it was wonderful to feel firm ground beneath our feet once more.
LW: beside = at the side of, next to
Our school was built right beside a river.
LW: behind = at the back (of)
I hung my coat behind the door.
LW: across = from one side to the other of something with clear limits, such as an area of land, a road, or a river
When I reached the river, I simply swam across.
XP: time is running out = used to say that there is not much time left in which to achieve something
Time is running out for the men trapped under the rubble.
XP: put sb off their stride = to take someone's attention away from what they are doing, so that they stop doing it or do it wrong
He interrupted mid-speech and it put me off my stride.
XP: In my opinion
In my opinion, we should pay more attention to the present state of affairs.
XP: in my view
So, in my view, it also includes protection against non-man-made threats, such as the effects of natural disasters.
XP: as/so far as I'm concerned = used to say what your personal opinion is about something
She can come whenever she likes, as far as I'm concerned.
XP: as/so far as I can tell = used to say what you have noticed or understood
There's been no change, as far as I can tell.
XP: as/so far as I know = used to say what you think is true, although you do not know all the facts
He isn't coming today, as far as I know.
XP: far be it from/for me to = I certainly would not
Far be it from me to tell you how to run your life.
XP: far from sth = certainly not something
The situation is far from clear.
XP: far from being/doing sth = used to describe something that is almost the opposite of something else
She insisted that, far from being easy, it would be a difficult period for all concerned.
XP: far from it = certainly not
He's not handsome - far from it.
XP: go so far as to do sth = to be willing to do something that is extreme
It's good, but I wouldn't go so far as to say that it's great.
XP: so far = until now
So far we've made £32,000.
XP: so far so good = used to say that an activity has gone well until now
I've found a tin of beans. So far so good, but where is the tin opener?
