XP: a while = a length of time
Oh, it was a while ago (= a long time ago) / You were there quite a while (= a long time), weren't you? / I only stayed for a short while. / I'll be fine in a while (= soon).
XP: in place (1) = If something is in place, it is in its usual or correct position
He screwed the shelf in place.
XP: in place (2) = organized
The arrangements are all in place for the concert next Thursday.
XP: in place (3, UK) = (of running or jumping) in one place without moving forward or backward at all
She looked like she was running in place as six women flew past her.
XP: in place (4) = without making any progress
While Maryland has been running in place or going backward, a number of states have courted filmmakers aggressively.
XP: in place of sb/sth = instead of someone or something
You can use margarine in place of butter in some recipes.
XP: take the place of sb/sth = to be used instead of someone or something
-----
XP take place = to happen
The concert takes place next Thursday.
XP: out of place = in the wrong place or looking wrong
The boy looked uncomfortable and out of place among the adults.
XP: by virtue of = because of; as a result of
She succeeded by virtue of her tenacity rather than her talent.
XP: the latter = the second of two people, things, or groups previously mentioned
She offered me more money or a car and I chose the latter.
XP: the former = the first of two people, things, or groups previously mentioned
Of the two suggestions, I prefer the former.
XP: further to (mainly UK formal) = used in business letters to refer to an earlier letter, conversation, meeting, etc.
Further to your letter of 11 March, I should like to inform you of a number of recent developments regarding the Saffron Hill site.
